            {
               "text": "<p><h3>Map Projections</h3>The fact that Earth is not flat does not mean we cannot represent it on a plane.</p>",
               "source": [],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "To create a map projection, we first need a scaled globe model of Earth. Using this model, we select a technique to transfer the spherical representation onto a two-dimensional surface, such as paper. The image in this section demonstrates the \"Developable Surface\", technique, which is used with projections like the Conic Projection with a Standard Parallel. However, this is just one of many available techniques. In the work by the National Council of Educational Research and Training, Lambert’s projection and Mercator’s projection are also discussed; these are widely used for creating world maps",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "2c731ac7-93ae-4e9b-98d6-6f28c7681735",
                     "text": "National Concil of Education Research and Training",
                     "page": "",
